TI  - Key factors of adopting 6D BIM in modular integrated construction for transition to circular economy practices: DEMATEL-FAHP methods
PY  - 2025
JO  - ARCHITECTURAL ENGINEERING AND DESIGN MANAGEMENT
DO  - 10.1080/17452007.2025.2585851
AB  - Research on the circular economy (CE) has gained increasing attention in the construction sector. While the integration of 6D Building Information Modeling (BIM) and Modular Integrated Construction (MIC) shows strong potential to facilitate CE practices, limited studies have prioritized and examined the causal relationships among the key factors (KFs) affecting the adoption of 6D BIM in MIC projects. Therefore, this study conducted a systematic literature review (SLR) of 45 peer-reviewed articles to identify the relevant KFs, followed by a hybrid analytical approach combining the Fuzzy Analytic Hierarchy Process (FAHP) for factor prioritization and the Decision-Making Trial and Evaluation Laboratory (DEMATEL) for cause-effect analysis through expert evaluation. The FAHP results revealed that Cost Factor, Optimized Cost Estimation, and Collaboration are the top-ranked KFs in promoting 6D BIM adoption within MIC projects. DEMATEL analysis further showed that Productivity, Software Maturity, and Cognition significantly influence the Cost Factor, while Customer Demand, Collaboration, Software Maturity, and Cognition affect Future Adaptability. These findings provide an analytical foundation for prioritizing strategic actions that enhance the effective implementation of 6D BIM-MIC integration toward achieving CE objectives.
